Governor Perdue,
This is a follow up to my conversation with your assistant Lesley concerning the need for NC SEPA to apply to Carolinas Cement.
My name is Dr. Robert Parr.  I am a specialist in Emergency Medicine and I have have practiced medicine in Wilmington since 1983.
Prior to my medical career I obtained an advanced degree in Biological Oceanography from Oregon State University where I studied the effects of industrial development on the marine environment.
During that period and afterward, I was directly involved with numerous environmental/industrial siting studies both nationally and overseas.
I am presently a member of the US Army Corps of Engineers Carolinas Cement Scoping/Stake Holder Committee. 
I have met numerous times with representatives of Carolinas Cement and I have personally visited Medley, Florida home of Titan America's Pennsuco cement plant on my own.
I have spoken on numerous occasions with representatives from the National Parks Conservation Association, who along with the Sierra Club and Natural Resources Defense Council have
been opposing TItan America's mining operations in Medley, Florida since 2002.




Briefly:
NC SEPA is a required for Carolinas Cement to protect human health and our local marine environment.  The legal requirements for enacting SEPA have been met  by this project.
In Florida Titan America's permit to mine in Medley, Florida has been overturned three times since 2002 for failing to protect the aquifer for Miami Dade County and for failing to properly mitigate wetlands destruction.
It is my opinion that the pending NC DAQ permit has not been crafted with necessary input from NC health professionals and NC marine resource specialists, whose responsibility it is to protect human health and our marine resources.  NC SEPA would require their input prior to any permitting decisions.  If NC DAQ has received written input from these NC professionals to date ask them to provide this information to your office and the general public at this time.
I have forwarded your office an open letter from Carolinas Cement chiding the NC Marine Fisheries Commission for the commission's request that NC SEPA apply to this matter.   The representatives of the Marine Fisheries Commission have one obligation and that is to protect the viability and health of our marine resources.  It is their respected opinion that NC SEPA is necessary in proceeding with any permitting at this stage.  Clearly a foreign owned, out of state company should not be lecturing our NC representatives on these matters. 
At the first public meeting in New Hanover County on April 21, 2008, representatives of Carolinas Cement and it's backers failed  to answer even basic questions regarding the environmental impacts of the proposed Carolinas Cement plant in Castle Hayne.   Nancy Pritchard, our County Commissioner who voted against the incentive package, did so because in her own words she was not provided with the necessary information on which to vote.  Numerous private citizens also asked for more detailed information at that meeting - information that was not forthcoming in a timely manner.
Only recently was it verified that on April 21, 2008, the same day of this meeting, the limestone mines at Titan America's Pensucco cement plant in Medley, Florida were closed by federal order for threatening the drinking water supply of Miami Dade County and failure to properly mitigate destruction to affected wetlands.

At the same time that Titan America was obtaining incentive grants from New Hanover County and working to obtain NC State grants from North Carolina, the Titan America mines in Florida were closed by court order.   This was vital and timely information that was withheld from public view seemingly to advance the needs of Carolinas Cement  at the expense of the people and resources of North Carolina.
Clearly this is not a company that should be allowed to evade NC SEPA by retrospective maneuvering, which may enhance the companies bottom line at the expense of the citizens of North Carolina. 

If you or your representatives would like to speak with me personally about these matters do not hesitate to contact me.  I can provide detailed reference sources for all above facts.

Thank you for your time and consideration of this important matter. 



