Dear Governer Perdue,
I'm writing to ask you and your administration to support efforts in the Legislature to slow down the fast track rush to impose a new coal burning cement plant and adjacent open pit limestone quarry on New Hanover County.  At the very least I ask you to not oppose such efforts.
The Carolinas Cement Co., a wholly owned subsidiary of Titan America, LLC, itself a subsidiary of the Titan Cement Company of Greece, has lately been flooding Raleigh with a mix of half truths and whole dollars in their efforts to have this project put on the fast track with minimal environmental oversight or regulation.  The scale of the proposed project, the very nature of the industry, and the location of the planned plants and quarries should all demand stricter regulatory oversight, not expedited approval.  At the very least the project needs to be considered as a whole at each stage of the permitting process.  Air permits should not be issued for construction of the plant without considering the associated mining operations and no permits should be issued before the full Environmental Impact Statement is released.
That there are no cement plants operating in North Carolina further raises the question as to our capacity to competently evaluate and regulate this industry at all.  I'm very worried that applying standards developed for small scale gravel operations or manufacturing facilities to such a large operation may be inadequate.  Sen. Boseman's proposal for a temporary moratorium on new Cement Plant construction until such issues can be addressed (S699) seems eminently reasonable.
I have heard it proposed that the State of North Carolina invited Titan Cement to build this plant and that imposing oversight would be taken as rude and unfriendly to business.  This is simply untrue.  The facts of the matter are that Titan America (and its predecessors and sudsidiaries) first purchased the property in question some 25 years ago, promising, at the time, to build a state of the art $75 million cement kiln.  That didn't happen.  They later announced plans once again build a new plant for the site (this time throwing around numbers in the $200 million range) but, once again, nothing happened.  The sad fact is that Castle Hayne, NC is not a particularly good place to locate a cement plant.  The layers of limestone needed to feed a cement kiln are all located well below the local water table.  The workforce is there, the transportation links are there, and the land is there, but the topography and geologoy of the Atlantic Coastal Plain with its swamps, wetlands, rivers and lack of elevation all make responsible mining operations prohibitively expensive.  (Irresponsible mining operations can still be cost effective, but that's the whole worry here.)
After 25 years of start and stop plans from Titan, will a one year moratorium really be that much of a hardship?  After a quarter century of planning and replanning, why is it now imperative to build a new plant on a crash basis?  At one point Titan shelved its construction plans simply because it was more profitable to rent out the exisiting facilities on that property as a movie set.  If you wonder what the inside of a cement plant looks like I direct your attention to the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles movies where the old plant served as the headquarters of "The Foot", the enemies of the heroes on the half shell.  I'm sure any further similarity between Titan Cement and an evil ninja clan behind a massive urban crime wave are purely coincidental.
Titan's PR machine has been hyping jobs as the #1 advantage of this new plant.  Again, the truth is less clear.  Cement is a very cyclical industry.  When times are good, cement is in demand and plants operate at capacity. When times are not good cement is not in demand and plants shut down for months at a time.  Long term, TItan promises jobs only when we don't need them.  Titan gets more support from its short term claims: the number of jobs it will bring to the area for plant construction.  Here there is some very short term truth: there will be construction jobs and construction jobs drive the economy of Southeastern North Carolina.  But consider also that Titan is building this plant in the northern part of the county.  New Hanover County is a fairly small (geographically) county and largely built up.  Our beach towns are built up.  Our urban areas are built up.  The region experiencing the most growth the past few years (and projected to continue that way for the forseeable future) is northern part of the county.  But putting a giant open pit mine and cement kiln will effectively end residential and commercial development in that part of the county.  Holly Shelter Road will cease to be the new focus of housing development and become a designated heavy industrial blight area, much like US421 to the NW of Wilmington is now.  We do NOT need another stretch of 421.  The building industry in this area is  in good position to rebound and get back to building houses - but not if we poison their fields like this.
I was particularly distressed some months ago to see the Commerce Department lined up to oppose Boseman's S699 and later to oppose Sen. Justice's motion to bring such plants under SEPA.  This disappointed me on two levels.  First, it absolutely flew in the face of the talk of "green jobs" and "green industry" we've been hearing from your administration and especially from your Commerce Department and its NC Economic Development Committee.  Talking about green jobs while at the same time greasing the skids for a particularly dirty industry in a particularly sensitive region was the kind of hypocrisy nobody wants to see from a new administration. 
Secondly, I view this as a largely local issue.  The local delegation to Raleigh has been united in their wishes to see things slowed down and thought out.  Titan does not have broad local support.  What local support they have is small and uncommitted.  It's now widely acknowledged that the County Commissioners erred when they extended an incentive package to Titan, relying on the kind of strict regulation and oversight that Titan now seems to be avoiding.  Titan is a decidedly unpopular player in this county and we wonder why the powers that be in Raleigh seem determined to force it down our throats?  From a purely political standpoint, I believe supporting this project is a mistake.
I close with the example of the Elgin Marbles.  In early 19th century Athens the lime and cement industry did not necessarily quarry for raw limestone to fuel their kilns.  They used whatever limestone or marble was to be found at hand.  There was quite a bit of limestone and marble lying about on the Acropolis: the old, abandoned greek temples.  Fallen pieces and other pieces easily removed (sculptures, friezes, pediments, columns, etc.) were carted off and burned down to lime and cement.  Between1801 and 1813 Lord Elgin, then British Ambassador to the Ottoman Empire, purchased, removed and shipped overseas much of the most precious statuary and friezes from the Acropolis.  These masterpieces of antiquity were later acquired by the British Museum where they were preserved and displayed for hundreds of years until, fairly recently, the Greek government began agitating for their return.  Where they should be displayed today is an issue for artists and international lawyers, but it is widely accepted that had Lord Elgin not removed the marble pieces they likely would have gone into an Athenian limeburners kiln and ended up as stucco for some 19th century mixed use development. 
The Northeast Cape Fear River and Island Creek (the beautiful and rich area where Titan wants to build and strip mine) and the aquifer beneath (which Titan wants to lower by a hundred feet or more to access the limestone) are our Elgin Marbles, our natural treasures, our birthright.  We have no imperialist British ambassador with paternal instincts to ship the river off for safekeeping until we come to our senses.  We don't even have a foursome of Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles ready to crawl out of the sewers to save us from the evil Foot.  We don't need them.  We do have a basic framework of environmental protection in place.  We can expand on what we have and enforce the finished product and protect ourselves, but we can't do that if Raleigh lacks the political will to stand up to the limeburners and others who would ignore what protections are already in place.
Please, Governor.  Let the system work.  There ought be no rush to strip mine Island Creek or drain our fresh water aquifer.  If the plan is a good one, it will still be a good one a year from now.  This proposed plant will be here for 100 years.  Let's take the time to get it right.
Sincerely,
